01:02:26.410 --> 01:02:27.954
I knew Jon Landau.

01:02:28.037 --> 01:02:29.664
He was managing
Bruce Springsteen.

01:02:29.747 --> 01:02:32.041
So, Jon came to me
and he said,

01:02:32.124 --> 01:02:34.168
"Can you think of something to do?"

01:02:35.586 --> 01:02:36.837
And then I got this idea

01:02:36.921 --> 01:02:39.340
of pulling this girl out of the audience
to dance with him.

01:02:39.423 --> 01:02:41.676
That's where Courteney Cox
came from.

01:02:41.759 --> 01:02:43.970
After the disaster
of <i>Body Double,</i>

01:02:44.053 --> 01:02:46.472
you start thinking about
what you're doing,

01:02:46.556 --> 01:02:49.642
and why are you getting
these kind of reactions.

01:02:49.767 --> 01:02:53.688
So, it was like, "I got to do something
completely different."

01:02:53.771 --> 01:02:55.773
♪♪

01:02:58.067 --> 01:03:00.695
I hadn't done a comedy
in a long time.

01:03:00.778 --> 01:03:04.240
And I really liked Danny DeVito.
He was attached to the movie.

01:03:04.323 --> 01:03:05.992
It's very difficult
to make a movie

01:03:06.075 --> 01:03:09.453
where the studio administration
did not sponsor it initially.

01:03:09.537 --> 01:03:12.248
We got through it.
They didn't want to release it.

01:03:12.331 --> 01:03:14.750
They didn't like the previews.

01:03:14.834 --> 01:03:16.711
It was just a struggle
all the way through.

01:03:16.794 --> 01:03:19.297
I liked it, it was a lot of fun.
It was a cute little comedy.

01:03:19.380 --> 01:03:22.800
It got some very good reviews,
so a lot of people really liked it.

01:03:22.883 --> 01:03:24.260
No, no, my friend.

01:03:24.343 --> 01:03:26.470
[both]
Thank <i>you</i>, Mr. Acavano.

01:03:26.554 --> 01:03:28.806
[De Palma] In the 80's,
I was working all the time.

01:03:28.889 --> 01:03:30.474
You know,
I was writing scripts.

01:03:30.558 --> 01:03:32.935
I was selling things.

01:03:33.019 --> 01:03:35.688
Some would get made.
Some wouldn't.

01:03:35.813 --> 01:03:39.233
Then I got involved with developing
<i>Fatal Attraction.</i>

01:03:39.317 --> 01:03:41.861
I was not sold on the way
the script was going

01:03:41.944 --> 01:03:43.487
and I said, "I'm out."

01:03:43.571 --> 01:03:46.991
Fortunately,
about 24 hours later,

01:03:47.074 --> 01:03:49.076
somebody over at Paramount

01:03:49.160 --> 01:03:51.287
suggested me to do
<i>The Untouchables.</i>

01:03:53.956 --> 01:03:55.791
Art developed the script
before I arrived

01:03:55.875 --> 01:03:59.211
and the three of us
worked on the script after that.

01:03:59.295 --> 01:04:01.881
Well, first we had to find
Elliott Ness.

01:04:01.964 --> 01:04:03.466
And I wanted to use Don Johnson,

01:04:03.549 --> 01:04:05.259
because I knew Don

01:04:05.343 --> 01:04:07.678
and he was very big in <i>Miami Vice now.</i>

01:04:07.762 --> 01:04:10.306
And Art felt very strongly
about Kevin.

01:04:10.389 --> 01:04:13.476
And then I called Spielberg,

01:04:13.559 --> 01:04:16.395
I called Larry Kasdan,
who had all worked with Kevin before,

01:04:16.479 --> 01:04:19.565
to reassure me about— this guy's
going to carry the whole movie.

01:04:19.649 --> 01:04:24.111
So they said, "Yes, this guy's
going to be something. Feel confident."

01:04:24.195 --> 01:04:27.490
Then we had Bob Hoskins
playing Al Capone.

01:04:27.573 --> 01:04:28.908
And then we got Sean in,

01:04:28.991 --> 01:04:30.826
because Sean
is always looking for things

01:04:30.910 --> 01:04:33.829
to get him out
of his James Bond character.

01:04:33.913 --> 01:04:37.124
And I saw Andy Garcia
in <i>8 Million Ways to Die.</i>

01:04:37.208 --> 01:04:38.584
♪♪

01:04:38.668 --> 01:04:42.380
And I was down in Chicago,
you know, with my boards,

01:04:42.463 --> 01:04:45.049
and figuring out how we're going
to shoot all this stuff.

01:04:45.132 --> 01:04:48.302
Meanwhile, I'm thinking
we've got this movie,

01:04:48.386 --> 01:04:52.306
except we—
it's— to me, it's like a—

01:04:52.390 --> 01:04:55.726
some kind of sophisticated
English playhouse theater.

01:04:55.810 --> 01:04:58.813
We need an American
gangster actor.

01:05:00.940 --> 01:05:03.234
What draws my admiration?

01:05:03.317 --> 01:05:04.944
What is that
which gives me joy?

01:05:05.027 --> 01:05:07.905
[all clamoring]

01:05:11.158 --> 01:05:12.827
- Baseball.
- [laughing]

01:05:14.704 --> 01:05:16.985
[De Palma] Bobby takes a long time
