01:10:04.493 --> 01:10:06.036
and who was going
to show up.

01:10:06.120 --> 01:10:09.081
And our big competition
was that movie

01:10:09.206 --> 01:10:12.793
where John Lithgow lives with
some kind of monster in the house.

01:10:12.876 --> 01:10:14.712
Everybody thought
<i>Harry and the Hendersons</i>

01:10:14.795 --> 01:10:16.088
<i>was going to be huge.</i>

01:10:16.213 --> 01:10:18.882
And we kind of blew everybody away
the first weekend.

01:10:18.966 --> 01:10:22.386
You know, <i>The Untouchables</i> was
another one of those magical movies.

01:10:23.387 --> 01:10:26.056
And very few happen
in your career.

01:10:27.474 --> 01:10:30.310
Then I get them to make a movie
that nobody wanted to make.

01:10:30.394 --> 01:10:34.148
This is the one, sarge.
She's the pretty one.

01:10:34.231 --> 01:10:35.691
Take the pretty one.

01:10:35.774 --> 01:10:37.693
[De Palma] I always felt
that <i>Casualties of War</i>

01:10:37.776 --> 01:10:40.571
was the best story
about the Vietnam War.

01:10:40.654 --> 01:10:42.614
It was a great piece
of journalism.

01:10:42.698 --> 01:10:45.492
It had a really dramatic arc to it.

01:10:45.576 --> 01:10:48.579
It felt very much the way I feel

01:10:48.662 --> 01:10:52.458
about these type of wars that we get into
and nobody knows why.

01:10:52.541 --> 01:10:54.460
To me, it's a metaphor
for what we're doing.

01:10:54.543 --> 01:10:56.336
We are raping
these countries.

01:10:56.420 --> 01:10:57.671
This is a weapon.

01:10:57.755 --> 01:11:00.132
[breathing heavily]

01:11:02.718 --> 01:11:03.969
This is a gun.

01:11:04.053 --> 01:11:06.722
And then you have a—
you know, a real incident

01:11:06.805 --> 01:11:10.184
in which an innocent
is raped and killed.

01:11:10.267 --> 01:11:13.228
This is what we're doing,
and we don't ever want to admit it.

01:11:13.312 --> 01:11:15.147
Nobody ever
talks about it anymore.

01:11:15.272 --> 01:11:17.483
We don't understand
these people.

01:11:17.566 --> 01:11:19.610
We don't understand
their culture.

01:11:19.693 --> 01:11:24.281
We're being fed a lot of mumbo jumbo
of the reasons that's important

01:11:24.364 --> 01:11:27.534
for our country's
self-interest to be there

01:11:27.618 --> 01:11:31.205
that makes absolutely no sense
whatsoever.

01:11:31.288 --> 01:11:33.248
And no wonder these people,

01:11:33.332 --> 01:11:38.504
these soldiers trying to do
the right thing, go crazy.

01:11:38.587 --> 01:11:41.632
People had been trying to make
<i>Casualties of War</i>

01:11:41.715 --> 01:11:43.383
since the early 70's.

01:11:43.467 --> 01:11:45.511
It's one of these properties
that was bought,

01:11:45.594 --> 01:11:48.055
developed, sat on a shelf,

01:11:48.138 --> 01:11:50.099
bought, developed,
sat on a shelf.

01:11:50.182 --> 01:11:52.768
Fortunately, Dawn had left Paramount

01:11:52.851 --> 01:11:54.394
and became
head of Columbia,

01:11:54.478 --> 01:11:58.982
and she was looking for a project
with a lot of big names.

01:11:59.066 --> 01:12:01.735
And Dawn used to run
Michael J. Fox's company,

01:12:01.819 --> 01:12:04.404
and she got Michael interested
in playing Eriksson,

01:12:04.488 --> 01:12:06.508
which is the only way the movie
would have ever gotten made.

01:12:06.532 --> 01:12:09.827
See, these people here,
they confuse themselves.

01:12:09.910 --> 01:12:11.221
Are they Cong, are they not Cong?

01:12:11.245 --> 01:12:15.332
Sean came up with this
very kind of macho Brooklyn guy

01:12:15.415 --> 01:12:17.167
and was literally the sarge.

01:12:17.251 --> 01:12:21.088
I mean, he treated the other actors
like they were in his squad.

01:12:21.171 --> 01:12:22.422
He never talked to Michael.

01:12:22.506 --> 01:12:25.068
His attitude about him was like
how he felt about him in the movie.

01:12:25.092 --> 01:12:26.652
Eriksson here
don't wanna ball the dink.

01:12:26.718 --> 01:12:28.011
- How come?
- I don't know.

01:12:28.095 --> 01:12:29.888
- He's a chickenshit.
- Is that it?

01:12:29.972 --> 01:12:31.431
Is that your problem,
Eriksson?

01:12:31.515 --> 01:12:33.684
[De Palma] Michael's
a very amiable guy,

01:12:33.767 --> 01:12:35.978
and he felt very much
like an outsider,

01:12:36.061 --> 01:12:38.313
you know, because of Sean
and his guys.

01:12:38.397 --> 01:12:39.898
But it worked very well
for the movie.

01:12:39.982 --> 01:12:41.984
♪♪

01:12:43.277 --> 01:12:47.364
There was a moment in the movie
where Michael hits Clark with a shovel.

01:12:47.447 --> 01:12:49.575
And Sean's kind of taunting him,
you know,

01:12:49.658 --> 01:12:51.952
with that wise-ass look he's got.

01:12:52.035 --> 01:12:53.370
And we did
a couple of takes.

01:12:53.453 --> 01:12:57.374
And then Sean walked up to Michael J.
and knocked him to the ground.

01:12:57.457 --> 01:13:00.586
Just knocked him down.

01:13:00.669 --> 01:13:03.172
And I thought Michael
was going to kill him.

01:13:03.255 --> 01:13:04.506
And then we shot the scene.

01:13:07.509 --> 01:13:09.303
It did bring something out in Michael

01:13:09.386 --> 01:13:12.890
that— that he was having
some difficulty getting to.

01:13:12.973 --> 01:13:14.224
I mean, he had all that anger,

01:13:14.308 --> 01:13:17.561
and then just Sean just pushed it
right over the top.

01:13:17.644 --> 01:13:19.730
And then, when he whispers to him
when he leaves,

01:13:19.813 --> 01:13:21.356
you know, about payback,

01:13:21.440 --> 01:13:24.109
I think he whispered once
to him, "Television actor."

01:13:24.193 --> 01:13:26.195
[laughs]

01:13:29.907 --> 01:13:32.284
Good old Sean.
Very exciting to work with.

01:13:32.409 --> 01:13:35.662
It— it was a very difficult movie
to make

01:13:35.746 --> 01:13:37.414
with the weather and the heat,

01:13:37.497 --> 01:13:41.418
and to understand Vietnam,
you've got to understand the terrain.

01:13:41.501 --> 01:13:42.878
You got to understand the heat.

01:13:42.961 --> 01:13:44.630
Once you get the heat,

01:13:44.713 --> 01:13:47.466
you can't imagine how that affects
the way you think.

01:13:47.549 --> 01:13:50.761
Then Thailand, I built
the whole jungle set

01:13:50.844 --> 01:13:54.848
because, the jungle, you walk three paces
and you could be anywhere.

01:13:54.932 --> 01:13:57.017
There's no orientation
in the jungle.

01:13:57.100 --> 01:13:58.894
So, I said,
"Let's build a jungle set

01:13:58.977 --> 01:14:01.230
and just basically move
the trees around."

01:14:01.313 --> 01:14:03.482
And Dawn actually traveled
all the way there.

01:14:03.565 --> 01:14:06.777
I think she lasted about five hours
and got in a plane and went home.

01:14:06.860 --> 01:14:08.862
It was awful.

01:14:09.863 --> 01:14:12.407
[screams]

01:14:12.491 --> 01:14:14.034
[De Palma]
I wanted to have that sense

01:14:14.117 --> 01:14:17.245
that if you thought things
were bad above ground,

01:14:17.329 --> 01:14:20.374
you should see what was going on
below ground.

01:14:20.457 --> 01:14:23.710
And the only way to do that
is to crane directly down

01:14:23.794 --> 01:14:26.421
and show a cutaway of the tunnel

01:14:26.505 --> 01:14:30.258
and the threat moving through it,
like an ant colony.

01:14:32.260 --> 01:14:34.721
Well, Columbia made me
preview the movie,

01:14:34.805 --> 01:14:37.474
but the previews
don't really help much at all.

01:14:37.557 --> 01:14:39.309
You get all this pressure
to do things,

01:14:39.393 --> 01:14:41.478
and, in retrospect,
you regret it terribly.

01:14:41.561 --> 01:14:43.188
At the end of <i>Casualties of War</i>

01:14:43.271 --> 01:14:45.399
I took out a couple
of the interrogation scenes,

01:14:45.482 --> 01:14:47.150
especially the one
where they—

01:14:47.234 --> 01:14:50.529
They ripped Michael apart
on the stand by the defense attorney.

01:14:50.612 --> 01:14:51.923
Isn't it true that what you went out to do

01:14:51.947 --> 01:14:54.717
is to figure out how to use this incident
to get the hell out of the infantry?

01:14:54.741 --> 01:14:56.118
- [man] Objection.
- Can you find—

01:14:56.201 --> 01:14:57.494
And I took that thing out.

01:14:57.577 --> 01:14:59.913
I ultimately put it back
in the revised version.

01:14:59.997 --> 01:15:04.543
Because if you put anything that makes
the audience react too strongly,

01:15:04.626 --> 01:15:05.919
they want you to take it out.

01:15:06.003 --> 01:15:08.171
My movies tend
to upset people a lot,

01:15:08.255 --> 01:15:11.758
so you can imagine the things
they're trying to take out of my movies.

01:15:11.842 --> 01:15:13.510
And I have to fight them
tooth and nail.

01:15:14.761 --> 01:15:18.765
A preview for this kind of movie
really doesn't tell you anything.

01:15:18.849 --> 01:15:23.186
I mean, the material is <i>so emotional</i>
and <i>so depressing.</i>

01:15:23.270 --> 01:15:24.855
What's a preview
going to tell you?

01:15:24.938 --> 01:15:27.399
I don't want to see the movie?
It disturbed me too much.

01:15:27.524 --> 01:15:29.359
I don't know what
to tell my friends?

01:15:29.443 --> 01:15:31.194
I find it hard
to look at it myself

01:15:31.278 --> 01:15:34.990
when you deal with material
that's very heartbreaking

01:15:35.073 --> 01:15:38.326
and you got to go to a mix and look
at that stuff over and over again.

01:15:38.410 --> 01:15:39.953
It's like <i>The Best Years of Our Lives</i>

01:15:40.037 --> 01:15:41.538
was on television the other day.

01:15:41.621 --> 01:15:43.381
There's an hour
of those poor guys, you know,

01:15:43.457 --> 01:15:45.375
just trying to adjust
to where they are.

01:15:45.459 --> 01:15:47.586
I mean, how do you look
at that movie?

01:15:47.669 --> 01:15:49.379
It's so upsetting.
Imagine making it.

01:15:49.463 --> 01:15:52.257
That's the feelings I have
on <i>Casualties of War.</i>

01:15:52.340 --> 01:15:54.426
Pauline wrote
a great review.

01:15:54.551 --> 01:15:58.013
But it didn't do well and there were a lot
of mixed reviews, you know.

01:15:58.096 --> 01:15:59.514
Nobody went to see it.

01:15:59.598 --> 01:16:04.936
It was a terrible disappointment after
all that work, and it was a lot of work.

01:16:07.105 --> 01:16:08.624
- [reporter 1] There he is.
- [reporter 2] There he is.

01:16:08.648 --> 01:16:11.401
- [female reporter] Let's go!
- [all clamoring]

01:16:11.485 --> 01:16:13.737
[De Palma] People never thought
I understood the book.

01:16:13.820 --> 01:16:15.447
I understood the book perfectly.

01:16:15.572 --> 01:16:18.617
Warners came to me
with <i>Bonfire of the Vanities.</i>

01:16:18.700 --> 01:16:20.660
And it was a chance
to go back to New York,

01:16:20.744 --> 01:16:22.329
make a big studio picture
and, you know,

01:16:22.412 --> 01:16:25.123
you go to work sometimes
just so you don't have to think.

01:16:25.207 --> 01:16:27.584
You see, my problem with
<i>Bonfire of the Vanities</i> is,

01:16:27.667 --> 01:16:30.754
it should have been like
<i>The Magnificent Ambersons.</i>

01:16:30.837 --> 01:16:33.590
You know, Sherman McCoy
is basically an asshole

01:16:33.673 --> 01:16:36.635
much like the lead character
in <i>Ambersons,</i>

01:16:36.718 --> 01:16:40.430
who destroys everything
because of his arrogance.

01:16:40.514 --> 01:16:42.641
And that's the way the movie
should've been.

01:16:42.724 --> 01:16:44.476
But then we wound up
with Tom Hanks,

01:16:44.601 --> 01:16:47.437
and so I think, "I'll take a gamble,
try to make him nicer."

01:16:47.521 --> 01:16:48.581
Just don't want to do anything stupid.

01:16:48.605 --> 01:16:51.441
If we keep our heads,
we'll be perfectly fine.

01:16:51.525 --> 01:16:53.044
[Maria Ruskin]
Oh, Jesus Christ, Sherman!

01:16:53.068 --> 01:16:54.778
We're in the middle
of a goddamn war zone

01:16:54.861 --> 01:16:56.947
and you're worried about
doing the right thing?

01:16:57.030 --> 01:16:59.366
[De Palma] I had all these
sort of thoughts in my mind.

01:16:59.449 --> 01:17:01.618
This is a very big,
expensive movie.

01:17:01.701 --> 01:17:04.412
I knew what could go wrong with it.

01:17:04.496 --> 01:17:06.915
It could go the way
of the Welles picture

01:17:06.998 --> 01:17:09.793
and it could also go the way
of <i>Sweet Smell of Success,</i>

01:17:09.876 --> 01:17:11.962
the greatest picture
Mackendrick ever made

01:17:12.045 --> 01:17:13.773
and it basically put him out
of the business.

01:17:13.797 --> 01:17:16.397
- You want some cheap, gruesome gags?
- You print them, don't you?

01:17:16.466 --> 01:17:19.761
<i>Bonfire</i> should have been
that tough, that cynical.

01:17:19.845 --> 01:17:23.014
But I said, "If I make that picture,
it's going to be a career ender."

01:17:23.098 --> 01:17:26.768
Like Welles,
like Mackendrick,

01:17:26.852 --> 01:17:28.895
I'm going to be
like, unemployable.

01:17:28.979 --> 01:17:31.273
And the irony is,
it still bombed.

01:17:31.356 --> 01:17:33.150
It should have been tougher, harder.

01:17:33.233 --> 01:17:35.735
Everybody that read the book
hated the movie.

01:17:35.819 --> 01:17:38.280
The problem of working
in the Hollywood system

01:17:38.363 --> 01:17:40.031
is the people are paid
a lot of money

01:17:40.115 --> 01:17:42.117
to get you to do
what they want you to do.

01:17:42.200 --> 01:17:43.827
That's why
they have those jobs.

01:17:43.910 --> 01:17:45.620
And you can lose your way

01:17:45.704 --> 01:17:48.165
and go along
with their concepts.

01:17:48.248 --> 01:17:53.503
I mean, I'd never seen stacks
of notes from the studio.

01:17:53.587 --> 01:17:56.715
That was like you know,
"Wow."

01:17:56.798 --> 01:18:01.011
I made a lot of compromises
and it was disaster.

01:18:01.094 --> 01:18:05.265
And Julie Salamon wrote
every move in it.

01:18:05.348 --> 01:18:08.977
I feel the movie, by itself,
stands up perfectly fine.

01:18:09.060 --> 01:18:11.271
Nothing wrong with the movie,
just don't read the book.

01:18:11.354 --> 01:18:16.318
I was leveled by the response
to <i>Bonfire of the Vanities.</i>

01:18:16.401 --> 01:18:19.613
Catastrophe.
Time to leave town.

01:18:19.821 --> 01:18:21.990
So, I got married.

01:18:22.073 --> 01:18:23.408
I had a child.

01:18:23.491 --> 01:18:25.577
And I went back to a genre

01:18:25.702 --> 01:18:29.039
that I had developed
in the 70's.

01:18:29.122 --> 01:18:30.832
♪♪

01:18:31.833 --> 01:18:33.084
I'm sorry.

01:18:34.502 --> 01:18:36.171
I'm sorry.

01:18:39.424 --> 01:18:42.135
My wife made a deal at Universal

01:18:42.219 --> 01:18:45.430
for us to make
a movie together.

01:18:45.513 --> 01:18:47.349
I had two ideas basically.

01:18:47.432 --> 01:18:50.769
One was a multiple personality
character.

01:18:50.852 --> 01:18:52.437
And many years before,

01:18:52.520 --> 01:18:55.774
I was having a relationship
with a woman that was married.

01:18:55.857 --> 01:18:59.152
And she used to come by
after work

01:18:59.236 --> 01:19:01.446
and, you know,
we would make love

01:19:01.529 --> 01:19:03.289
and because she was tired,
she'd fall asleep.

01:19:03.323 --> 01:19:05.283
And I remember
watching her sleeping, thinking,

01:19:05.367 --> 01:19:08.578
"What would happen if I just let her
sleep all night?

01:19:08.662 --> 01:19:11.122
How would you explain that
to your husband?"

01:19:11.206 --> 01:19:13.458
Oh, my God.

01:19:13.541 --> 01:19:17.212
But the problem was that
the Lolita Davidovich story,

01:19:17.295 --> 01:19:20.257
which should have been
the first story in <i>Raising Cain,</i>

01:19:20.340 --> 01:19:22.133
not the John Lithgow story

01:19:22.217 --> 01:19:26.179
with the kidnapping children
and the multiple personalities.

01:19:26.263 --> 01:19:28.181
That's what's supposed
to emerge later.

01:19:28.265 --> 01:19:31.768
It should have started with her
going to the shop to buy the clocks.

01:19:31.851 --> 01:19:33.603
She meets Steven Bauer.

01:19:33.687 --> 01:19:36.022
But when I was putting
the movie together,

01:19:36.106 --> 01:19:39.317
the John Lithgow stuff
was so strong, and the sort of—

01:19:39.401 --> 01:19:41.778
I guess you'd say
soap opera love story

01:19:41.861 --> 01:19:44.197
was not
the strongest element.

01:19:44.281 --> 01:19:48.618
I had to pull the whole John Lithgow stuff
forward into the movie.

01:19:48.702 --> 01:19:53.206
And that's why it has
a particular oddness to it.

01:19:53.290 --> 01:19:55.917
Because it's not put together
the way it was conceived.

01:19:56.001 --> 01:19:59.004
I don't know why I always cast
John Lithgow as villains.

01:19:59.087 --> 01:20:03.425
It's like, why did Billy Wilder
always cast Fred MacMurray as a villain

01:20:03.508 --> 01:20:06.678
when everybody else wanted him
as the professor in <i>Flubber?</i>

01:20:06.803 --> 01:20:08.930
And it was all shot
in our backyard.

01:20:09.014 --> 01:20:13.184
I mean, all the locations are
around the corner from where we lived.

01:20:13.268 --> 01:20:15.270
Gale and I got houses
up there.

01:20:15.353 --> 01:20:17.022
Lolita was born,
my daughter,

01:20:17.105 --> 01:20:20.400
and we were literally walking
outside the house and shooting.

01:20:20.483 --> 01:20:23.153
It was one of my most
financially successful movies,

01:20:23.236 --> 01:20:26.781
because I had, like, 10%
of the gross from the first dollar.

01:20:26.865 --> 01:20:30.201
It's interesting to look at the movie now
because it's like a family album.

01:20:30.285 --> 01:20:32.120
Where's Daddy?

01:20:32.203 --> 01:20:34.914
Daddy's not here, sweetie.
He's gone away.

01:20:34.998 --> 01:20:38.460
- Daddy's here.
- No, he's not.

01:20:38.543 --> 01:20:40.503
Come on, honey,
we've got to get back.

01:20:40.587 --> 01:20:42.213
Come to Mommy.

01:20:42.297 --> 01:20:44.299
♪♪

01:20:50.013 --> 01:20:52.682
Gale and I fell together
at a certain time in our lives

01:20:52.766 --> 01:20:57.228
and then basically went back to the lives
that we hadn't finished.

01:20:57.312 --> 01:21:03.443
And we had this remarkable daughter
in the process, so...

01:21:05.362 --> 01:21:08.323
it worked out rather well,
as strange as it may seem.

01:21:08.406 --> 01:21:09.866
♪♪

01:21:09.949 --> 01:21:12.660
That's when I got
the <i>Carlito's Way</i> script.

01:21:15.038 --> 01:21:18.124
And I thought,
"Oh, boy, here we go.

01:21:18.208 --> 01:21:22.504
Al Pacino,
Spanish speaking gangsters."

01:21:22.587 --> 01:21:25.382
But the script was so good
when I finally read it,

01:21:25.465 --> 01:21:28.176
I said, "I know how to make this
into a great movie."

01:21:28.259 --> 01:21:30.011
[indistinct chattering]

01:21:30.095 --> 01:21:33.598
Dick Sylbert is one of the great
production designers,

01:21:33.681 --> 01:21:35.892
a magical guy
to work with.

01:21:35.975 --> 01:21:37.936
The idea of the club
being like a boat

01:21:38.019 --> 01:21:41.564
came from the first
exterior location we found,

01:21:41.648 --> 01:21:45.735
which was a nightclub that was
in the shape of a boat.

01:21:45.819 --> 01:21:48.947
So then Dick designed the interior
to go with that exterior.

01:21:49.030 --> 01:21:51.950
And of course what happened was
that we lost the location.

01:21:52.033 --> 01:21:54.577
So, we didn't have
that boat-like exterior,

01:21:54.661 --> 01:21:58.498
but then it became an image
for Carlito going to the Caribbean.

01:21:58.581 --> 01:22:01.626
Sean, he did that hair thing,
just surprised us all.

01:22:01.709 --> 01:22:05.672
I had no idea he was going to come back
with the frizzed, shaved back head.

01:22:05.755 --> 01:22:10.135
Look at you, huh?
Really made something of your life.

01:22:10.218 --> 01:22:13.012
You know, I don't know if you've had
this experience with actors,

01:22:13.096 --> 01:22:15.265
but there's one scene
they fixate on,

01:22:15.348 --> 01:22:17.725
and that was the hospital scene
in <i>Carlito's Way.</i>

01:22:17.809 --> 01:22:21.396
We were rewriting that scene
to the day we shot it,

01:22:21.479 --> 01:22:23.565
and they were still unhappy with it.

01:22:23.648 --> 01:22:28.027
Relax, Dave.
It's your pal.

01:22:28.111 --> 01:22:29.988
[De Palma] We've got to get
all the mechanics

01:22:30.071 --> 01:22:31.698
of this movie-making
out of the way

01:22:31.781 --> 01:22:33.408
so the actors can act.

01:22:33.491 --> 01:22:36.244
If I see something
that's distracting somebody

01:22:36.327 --> 01:22:39.330
or making them lose
their concentration,

01:22:39.414 --> 01:22:41.583
you got to get to it
and get it out of their way.

01:22:41.666 --> 01:22:44.043
Being a director
is being a watcher,

01:22:44.127 --> 01:22:47.881
in the sense that you have
a lot of egos in the room

01:22:47.964 --> 01:22:51.342
and you have to sort of watch
how they interact with each other.

01:22:51.426 --> 01:22:54.053
Because when you're on a set,
you're basically concentrating

01:22:54.137 --> 01:22:57.599
on what's happening at the moment
and you've got to look at everything.

01:22:57.682 --> 01:23:00.143
You don't have time, you know,
say, "How's the coffee?"

01:23:00.226 --> 01:23:03.313
Or "Did you have
a nice night last night?"

01:23:03.396 --> 01:23:06.316
Your job as a director
is to get the movie made.

01:23:06.399 --> 01:23:08.735
You know, if somebody loses
their temper

01:23:08.818 --> 01:23:12.113
or you lose your temper,
everything stops.

01:23:12.197 --> 01:23:14.199
♪♪

01:23:23.625 --> 01:23:25.126
You know,
that chase we shot

01:23:25.210 --> 01:23:27.962
like, in the depths
of the summer

01:23:28.046 --> 01:23:32.258
and I was trying to get
this shot from train to train.

01:23:32.342 --> 01:23:35.470
And of course, Al's wearing this
very heavy leather jacket.

01:23:35.553 --> 01:23:36.804
Now, it's, you know,

01:23:36.888 --> 01:23:41.768
110 degrees in the subway
in the middle of the summer,

01:23:41.851 --> 01:23:43.770
and I'm in one train,
you know,

01:23:43.853 --> 01:23:46.856
trying to get a shot of him
racing through the other train

01:23:46.940 --> 01:23:48.399
being followed
by these guys

01:23:48.483 --> 01:23:50.163
and, of course,
you're going train to train

01:23:50.235 --> 01:23:52.237
and then you've got
all the posts.

01:23:52.320 --> 01:23:55.573
And do you— Is your train
going fast enough

01:23:55.657 --> 01:23:59.536
to just hold him in the shot
or does it get like this?

01:23:59.619 --> 01:24:02.914
So, we literally tried to get
this shot all night.

01:24:03.039 --> 01:24:05.500
And Al is running up and down
this train.

01:24:05.583 --> 01:24:08.419
And finally, it was about,
I don't know, 4:00 in the morning,

01:24:08.503 --> 01:24:13.299
and suddenly the train that Al's in
suddenly keeps going.

01:24:13.383 --> 01:24:16.636
Just disappears.
[laughing]

01:24:16.719 --> 01:24:20.723
And I said to my AD, Chris,
I said, "What happened?"

01:24:20.807 --> 01:24:24.394
And he said,
"Al took the train home."

01:24:24.477 --> 01:24:26.479
[laughing]

01:24:27.522 --> 01:24:31.317
"And he thinks you're crazy.
He doesn't know what you're doing."

01:24:31.401 --> 01:24:36.072
So, I had to get in my train
and go back to where Al's train was.

01:24:36.155 --> 01:24:40.076
And I went up to Al's trailer
and he's like, red,

01:24:40.159 --> 01:24:43.204
because he's been sweating with his coat,
you know, for hours.

01:24:43.288 --> 01:24:45.957
And he says,
"What are you doing?"

01:24:46.082 --> 01:24:48.084
♪♪

01:24:51.713 --> 01:24:54.299
You have to deal
with what happens on the day,

01:24:54.382 --> 01:24:56.843
and, of course, adjust your vision

01:24:56.926 --> 01:25:00.763
and come up with something that works
and maybe something that's better.

01:25:00.847 --> 01:25:05.977
I had elaborate storyboards
of this whole shoot-out on the escalators

01:25:06.102 --> 01:25:08.662
that were in the World Trade Center
that went down to the subway.

01:25:08.730 --> 01:25:12.734
I'd spent weeks
and weeks photographing.

01:25:12.817 --> 01:25:15.612
And I had
an architectural program

01:25:15.695 --> 01:25:18.072
and I built everybody
in all the positions.

01:25:18.156 --> 01:25:21.367
And then about a couple of days
before we were supposed to shoot it,

01:25:21.451 --> 01:25:24.203
they blew it up.
The first terrorist attack.

01:25:24.287 --> 01:25:26.265
So then, everybody said,
"What are we going to do?"

01:25:26.289 --> 01:25:29.584
And I said, "Suppose he goes
to Grand Central Station

01:25:29.667 --> 01:25:31.794
and gets on a train
to go to Florida.

01:25:31.878 --> 01:25:34.339
So, we'll do it
in Grand Central Station."

01:25:34.422 --> 01:25:38.384
And then I worked out that incredibly
complicated Steadicam shot with Al.

01:25:38.468 --> 01:25:40.470
♪♪

01:25:52.065 --> 01:25:53.566
[man]
Hey, Vinnie.

01:25:53.650 --> 01:25:55.401
Vinnie, wait up.

01:26:01.407 --> 01:26:03.660
[De Palma] The thing you learn
about the long take is

01:26:03.743 --> 01:26:09.874
that you can document the emotion
happening on the screen in real time.

01:26:09.957 --> 01:26:11.834
And once you start cutting
things up,

01:26:11.918 --> 01:26:15.254
you lose the emotional rhythm
of things.

01:26:15.338 --> 01:26:17.965
[thug] He ain't up here,
let's go down. Come on.

01:26:18.049 --> 01:26:21.070
[De Palma] The whole way the movie is
set up with the death being a flashback

01:26:21.094 --> 01:26:22.345
was an idea, you know,

01:26:22.428 --> 01:26:26.099
from the 27,000 <i>noir</i> pictures
I'd ever seen.

01:26:26.182 --> 01:26:28.518
That extremely tricky
opening shot

01:26:28.601 --> 01:26:31.938
which we had to, you know,
design a piece of equipment to do.

01:26:32.021 --> 01:26:34.357
You would wind up going
the wrong direction once,

01:26:34.440 --> 01:26:37.318
so it's not how
you usually operate things.

01:26:37.402 --> 01:26:40.530
We had to do this many times
to get it right.

01:26:40.613 --> 01:26:43.825
I wanted to get back
to the same scene

01:26:43.908 --> 01:26:46.119
with the audience
not realizing it.

01:26:46.202 --> 01:26:47.680
I wanted to, you know,
do a whole thing

01:26:47.704 --> 01:26:49.664
where it comes all the way back
to the beginning,

01:26:49.747 --> 01:26:52.875
but you don't realize you're in that scene
until you're, like, halfway into it,

01:26:52.959 --> 01:26:54.728
and you go, "Oh my God,
I've been here before."

01:26:54.752 --> 01:26:56.754
♪♪

01:27:05.596 --> 01:27:07.849
Again, it was getting
kind of mixed reviews,

01:27:07.932 --> 01:27:11.102
you know,
"tired genre gangsters."

01:27:11.227 --> 01:27:13.229
You know, and I was
kind of very disappointed,

01:27:13.312 --> 01:27:16.190
because I remember
when I went to Berlin

01:27:16.274 --> 01:27:19.110
and I was watching it in Berlin
after it opened

01:27:19.235 --> 01:27:21.112
and did okay
in the United States,

01:27:21.237 --> 01:27:23.573
I remember watching in Berlin,
and said, "I can't make—

01:27:23.656 --> 01:27:25.658
I can't make a better picture
than this."

01:27:25.742 --> 01:27:27.744
♪♪

01:27:34.751 --> 01:27:38.588
[ <i>Mission Impossible</i> theme plays]

01:27:38.671 --> 01:27:40.006
Again, it's a matter of being

01:27:40.089 --> 01:27:41.758
in the right place at the right time.

01:27:41.841 --> 01:27:43.760
Mike Ovitz called me up and said,

01:27:43.843 --> 01:27:46.846
"You interested in doing <i>Mission:
Impossible</i> with Tom Cruise?"

01:27:46.929 --> 01:27:50.391
I said, "Are you kidding?
Of course!"

01:27:50.475 --> 01:27:53.853
Because I was— I was determined
to make a huge hit.

01:27:53.936 --> 01:27:55.480
I said, "With Tom Cruise?

01:27:55.563 --> 01:27:57.273
<i>Mission: Impossible?</i>
I'm ready."

01:27:57.356 --> 01:28:01.611
So, this was a situation
where whatever Tom wanted to do,

01:28:01.694 --> 01:28:04.030
they would make.
They didn't care.

01:28:04.113 --> 01:28:06.741
They just want to make Tom Cruise
in <i>Mission: Impossible.</i>

01:28:06.824 --> 01:28:09.952
Tom, on the other hand, of course,
his first picture he's producing,

01:28:10.036 --> 01:28:11.621
wanted it to be exactly right.

01:28:11.704 --> 01:28:13.581
So, I got a hold of David Koepp,

01:28:13.664 --> 01:28:16.000
who wrote <i>Carlito's Way,</i>
to do the script.

01:28:16.083 --> 01:28:18.586
When we got through
the David Koepp script

01:28:18.669 --> 01:28:21.214
and they liked the script,
Tom, of course, had—

01:28:21.297 --> 01:28:23.883
he had things, character things
that were bothering him,

01:28:23.966 --> 01:28:25.802
he wasn't happy with.

01:28:25.885 --> 01:28:28.346
I said, "Tom, you've got to walk
into Shari's office with me

01:28:28.429 --> 01:28:31.265
and say you want to make this movie
or we're going nowhere."

01:28:31.349 --> 01:28:35.895
And I finally got him
to say yes, he'd make—

01:28:35.978 --> 01:28:37.563
he would make this script.

01:28:37.647 --> 01:28:41.859
The next phone call I got the next morning
was a call from Paula,

01:28:41.943 --> 01:28:44.445
and she said, "The good news
is we're go picture.

01:28:44.529 --> 01:28:47.073
The bad news is
we're firing David Koepp

01:28:47.156 --> 01:28:49.534
and we're bringing on
Robert Towne.

01:28:49.617 --> 01:28:52.578
Tom felt that Towne could bring
some character things to it.

01:28:52.662 --> 01:28:57.500
Well, how do you convey this
to your... pal?

01:28:59.252 --> 01:29:03.256
"Dave, the good news is
we're making the picture.

01:29:03.339 --> 01:29:05.466
The bad news is
you're fired."

01:29:05.550 --> 01:29:06.801
[laughs]

01:29:06.884 --> 01:29:10.096
So, we're getting to make the movie,
but I'm keeping in touch with Dave.

01:29:10.179 --> 01:29:12.056
I'm telling him everything
that's going on.

01:29:12.139 --> 01:29:14.392
I'm not happy with what
Bob Towne is doing.

01:29:14.475 --> 01:29:17.895
Towne's attitude basically was
to rewrite the whole script,

01:29:17.979 --> 01:29:19.564
which was wrong.

01:29:19.647 --> 01:29:21.858
And I'm getting to a point
where we're building sets

01:29:21.941 --> 01:29:23.985
and we don't know if these are
in the movie or not.

01:29:24.068 --> 01:29:27.738
What happened ultimately was that
I had made it quite evident to them

01:29:27.822 --> 01:29:30.867
that we could not go
with this Towne script.

01:29:30.950 --> 01:29:33.327
Dave had to come back
and rewrite the script.

01:29:33.411 --> 01:29:36.163
I literally had one screenwriter
in one hotel

01:29:36.247 --> 01:29:40.126
and another screenwriter
in another hotel writing simultaneously.

01:29:40.209 --> 01:29:44.255
Never in my history of making movies
has this ever happened to me.

01:29:44.380 --> 01:29:47.216
<i>Mission: Impossible</i> was originally set
in the United States and I said,

01:29:47.300 --> 01:29:50.636
"Tom, this is
<i>Mission: Impossible</i>!

01:29:50.720 --> 01:29:52.221
We can go all over the world!

01:29:52.305 --> 01:29:54.992
You know, there are these big,
huge movie stars in all these countries

01:29:55.016 --> 01:29:56.267
who are dying to be in this."

01:29:56.392 --> 01:29:58.853
Because Tom wanted to star
in <i>Mission: Impossible</i>

01:29:58.936 --> 01:30:00.479
and because <i>Mission: Impossible</i>

01:30:00.563 --> 01:30:03.566
is basically about a team of specialists,

01:30:03.649 --> 01:30:06.027
now, we've got to turn this
into a Tom Cruise movie.

01:30:06.110 --> 01:30:09.322
So I said, "Well, the first thing we have
to do is kill off the whole team."

01:30:15.119 --> 01:30:18.456
I saw Tom Cruise
in three incredible set pieces.

01:30:18.539 --> 01:30:20.958
Most spy thrillers
are crime thrillers,

01:30:21.042 --> 01:30:23.753
where you have a lot
of interesting character scenes

01:30:23.836 --> 01:30:26.881
where you're kind of
unwrapping the onion.

01:30:26.964 --> 01:30:29.091
Wrapping, another wrapping,
oh, and you find out,

01:30:29.175 --> 01:30:30.485
then you go over there
and you find som—

01:30:30.509 --> 01:30:31.761
Oh, but he really was—

01:30:31.844 --> 01:30:33.471
You know,
all this sort of stuff.

01:30:33.554 --> 01:30:34.805
But that isn't essentially

01:30:34.889 --> 01:30:40.311
something you can put
into a great visual set piece.

01:30:40.436 --> 01:30:41.812
I mean, the whole idea of McGuffin

01:30:41.896 --> 01:30:44.291
just doesn't make any difference
what they're chasing after...

01:30:44.315 --> 01:30:47.735
[man] <i>He has stolen one half
of a CIA NOC list,</i>

01:30:47.818 --> 01:30:50.863
<i>record of all our deep cover agents
working in Eastern—</i>

01:30:50.947 --> 01:30:53.282
Our little treasure here
has a belly full of microfilm.

01:30:53.366 --> 01:30:55.086
[De Palma]
...before we can get them moving.

01:30:55.117 --> 01:30:56.452
Oh, Mount Rushmore!

01:30:56.535 --> 01:30:58.135
What a great place
to have a chase scene!

01:30:58.204 --> 01:31:00.122
How do I get them
to Mount Rushmore?

01:31:00.206 --> 01:31:02.083
You get a really strong
visual idea.

01:31:02.166 --> 01:31:03.626
And then get the writer to come in

01:31:03.709 --> 01:31:06.170
or yourself to figure it out
to fill in the character

01:31:06.253 --> 01:31:08.381
that will get you
to Mount Rushmore.

01:31:08.464 --> 01:31:13.302
And I came up with the idea of going
into the CIA and the silent sequence...

01:31:18.849 --> 01:31:21.143
...getting the NOC list
out of the computer...

01:31:24.188 --> 01:31:27.191
...catching the sweat,
all that stuff.

01:31:27.274 --> 01:31:28.943
[grunting]

01:31:38.077 --> 01:31:41.080
I had worked out this very elaborate
end sequence

01:31:41.163 --> 01:31:44.834
with this helicopter chasing
the train into the tunnel.

01:31:44.917 --> 01:31:47.795
And Towne had thought
that it should be resolved

01:31:47.878 --> 01:31:54.009
with this pulling masks off
in the boxcar room.

01:31:54.093 --> 01:31:57.012
And we were getting
into a big—

01:31:57.096 --> 01:31:59.640
how should I say?
Conflict over it.

01:31:59.724 --> 01:32:01.809
I said, "You can't end
<i>Mission: Impossible</i>

01:32:01.892 --> 01:32:05.396
with people pulling masks off
in a boxcar!"

01:32:05.521 --> 01:32:07.773
And then, I think Towne said,
you know, like,

01:32:07.857 --> 01:32:11.068
"What are we going to have, helicopters
flying into tunnels or something?"

01:32:11.152 --> 01:32:14.363
I mean, brushing off
all these pyrotechnics

01:32:14.447 --> 01:32:18.284
as some kind of cheap
action sequence

01:32:18.367 --> 01:32:22.121
that had no emotional
or character thrust to it.

01:32:22.204 --> 01:32:25.958
So, we were basically
sort of arguing in front of Tom,

01:32:26.041 --> 01:32:28.502
and I finally said,
"Okay, guys.

01:32:28.586 --> 01:32:31.005
Boxcars, I love them.

01:32:31.088 --> 01:32:33.799
Masks pulling off,
let's do it.

01:32:33.883 --> 01:32:39.722
I'll throw out— I won't have to shoot all
this helicopter and tunnels and trains.

01:32:39.805 --> 01:32:43.225
We'll just have this wonderful
three-character scene in the boxcar.

01:32:43.309 --> 01:32:45.728
It'll be fantastic."
And I sort of left.

01:32:45.811 --> 01:32:49.273
And Tom basically decided

01:32:49.356 --> 01:32:53.444
that he thought that maybe
the action end of the movie

01:32:53.569 --> 01:32:55.446
would be better
than the boxcars.

01:32:55.571 --> 01:32:58.866
So, we had an abbreviated scene
in the boxcar.

01:32:58.949 --> 01:33:02.703
And then we got on top of the train
and did the end sequence.

01:33:02.787 --> 01:33:04.205
We built three cars,

01:33:04.288 --> 01:33:06.749
and it's all green screen
and, you know,

01:33:06.832 --> 01:33:08.959
all the ILM guys were there,

01:33:09.043 --> 01:33:11.378
you know, putting marks
all over everything.

01:33:11.462 --> 01:33:13.899
Very easy to make because I have
all this technical background.

01:33:13.923 --> 01:33:15.925
♪♪

01:33:22.431 --> 01:33:25.351
Here's— Here's a very bad thing
that's going on now

01:33:25.434 --> 01:33:28.979
in relation to sort of
the action sequences,

01:33:29.063 --> 01:33:33.234
and this is why they're so boring
in so many of these big movies,

01:33:33.317 --> 01:33:36.153
is that they're previsualized.

01:33:36.237 --> 01:33:40.908
Otherwise, well, we have the chase,
the car, and the dinosaur jumps over.

01:33:40.991 --> 01:33:45.246
And they throw it over to the—
you know, ILM, whoever does it.

01:33:45.329 --> 01:33:48.916
And the guys
previsualize it for you,

01:33:48.999 --> 01:33:51.252
because the shots
are so expensive.

01:33:51.335 --> 01:33:54.922
And they've got it all on their computers,
so what are you going to get?

01:33:57.842 --> 01:34:00.719
Many visual clichés.

01:34:00.803 --> 01:34:04.723
Something blowing up
and it coming right by the camera.

01:34:04.807 --> 01:34:07.560
All these little things
they have in their computers.

01:34:07.643 --> 01:34:09.645
Mission: Impossible's
<i>like</i> The Untouchables.

01:34:09.728 --> 01:34:11.480
I mean, it was like—
It worked.

01:34:11.564 --> 01:34:13.774
<i>Dressed to Kill,</i> it worked.
Everything worked.

01:34:13.858 --> 01:34:15.526
Everybody was overjoyed with it.

01:34:15.651 --> 01:34:17.695
They all knew
it was going to be a huge hit.

01:34:17.778 --> 01:34:20.281
And they basically
left us alone.

01:34:20.489 --> 01:34:22.491
I had the biggest hit
of my career

01:34:22.575 --> 01:34:25.828
but unfortunately,
my marriage fell apart

01:34:25.911 --> 01:34:28.956
and it was in the tabloids,
so I went into hiding.

01:34:29.039 --> 01:34:31.709
And from there,
in New York,

01:34:31.792 --> 01:34:34.420
I started to come up
with the idea

01:34:34.503 --> 01:34:36.088
with David for <i>Snake Eyes.</i>

01:34:36.171 --> 01:34:38.215
I always want to do something
in a casino.

01:34:38.299 --> 01:34:41.552
It's a whole insular life
and it's a corrupt world.

01:34:41.677 --> 01:34:43.679
See, when we have
these little visits,

01:34:43.762 --> 01:34:46.682
- I allow you, I permit you...
- Ow!

01:34:46.765 --> 01:34:49.101
...I give you the opportunity
to pay

01:34:49.184 --> 01:34:51.437
for all the extra police work
that you create!

01:34:51.520 --> 01:34:54.648
And doing this incredibly
complicated Steadicam shot,

01:34:54.732 --> 01:34:57.234
where it goes on for,
I don't know, 16, 18 minutes,

01:34:57.318 --> 01:35:00.112
you know, with all these cuts
buried and swish pans.

01:35:00.195 --> 01:35:03.574
So, you get a sense
of the world that he is king of

01:35:03.699 --> 01:35:07.453
before the secretary
is assassinated.

01:35:07.536 --> 01:35:10.998
We got this kind of <i>Rashomon</i> idea
that I always wanted to do.

01:35:11.081 --> 01:35:14.126
And we have to see it
from three different points of view,

01:35:14.209 --> 01:35:16.962
which is always something
that fascinates one.

01:35:17.046 --> 01:35:19.506
You know, again, this is a very
Hitchcockian thing.

01:35:19.590 --> 01:35:22.968
I had this idea,
"Well, I'll just show the prize fight

01:35:23.052 --> 01:35:25.804
from Nic Cage's point of view
but I'll never show the fight."

01:35:25.888 --> 01:35:27.139
Everybody will hear it.

01:35:27.222 --> 01:35:29.141
- [all cheering]
- [man] All right!

01:35:29.224 --> 01:35:30.851
- Yeah!
- [announcer] Holy cow!

01:35:30.935 --> 01:35:32.686
Everybody will be reacting to it.

01:35:32.770 --> 01:35:35.522
[all chattering]

01:35:36.649 --> 01:35:38.192
But nobody will see it.

01:35:38.275 --> 01:35:40.402
Hello? What?

01:35:40.486 --> 01:35:43.238
Who are you? Where?

01:35:43.322 --> 01:35:44.865
My lucky number?

01:35:44.949 --> 01:35:46.200
- [gunshot]
- [woman screams]

01:35:46.283 --> 01:35:47.785
What?

01:35:56.251 --> 01:35:58.253
You have to know
where everything is.

01:35:58.337 --> 01:35:59.922
And, you know,
and when you—

01:36:00.005 --> 01:36:02.383
So many times when,
you know, somebody fires

01:36:02.466 --> 01:36:04.802
and somebody falls down,
I mean, you know,

01:36:04.885 --> 01:36:06.762
it's like, "Where is everybody?

01:36:06.845 --> 01:36:10.182
How close are they?
How close is the jeopardy?"

01:36:10.265 --> 01:36:12.518
I'm scrupulous about that.

01:36:12.601 --> 01:36:16.480
My concept, and the concept
that Dave and I had,

01:36:16.563 --> 01:36:19.525
is that when you're dealing with
such corruption,

01:36:19.608 --> 01:36:22.236
you need God to come down

01:36:22.319 --> 01:36:24.655
and— and— and blow
it all away.

01:36:24.780 --> 01:36:26.782
It's the only thing
that works.

01:36:26.865 --> 01:36:29.368
That was the whole idea
of the wave.

01:36:29.451 --> 01:36:31.286
Holy shit.

01:36:36.792 --> 01:36:38.043
[screaming]

01:36:40.045 --> 01:36:42.256
I'm sorry, baby. I tried.

01:36:44.299 --> 01:36:46.593
- Look out!
- Jesus Chri—

01:36:48.137 --> 01:36:49.388
Look out!

01:36:53.183 --> 01:36:54.435
[screaming]

01:37:07.823 --> 01:37:09.801
[De Palma] And, of course,
nobody thought it worked,

01:37:09.825 --> 01:37:11.452
so we came up
with something else,

01:37:11.535 --> 01:37:14.830
which I never particularly thought worked
as well as the original idea.

01:37:20.711 --> 01:37:22.838
Endings are tough.
They're always tough.

01:37:22.921 --> 01:37:26.759
In your career, if you can get two or
three great endings to your movies,

01:37:26.842 --> 01:37:29.261
you're— it's a miracle.

01:37:29.344 --> 01:37:30.929
It was basically
a disappointment.

01:37:31.013 --> 01:37:33.223
It didn't get reviewed
particularly well.

01:37:33.307 --> 01:37:35.809
<i>Snake Eyes</i>
wasn't that expensive.

01:37:35.893 --> 01:37:40.397
I don't think it cost more than
$30 or $40 million or something.

01:37:40.481 --> 01:37:43.150
<i>Mission to Mars</i> was very expensive.
It cost 100.

01:37:43.484 --> 01:37:44.735
That's another situation

01:37:44.860 --> 01:37:46.463
where they have a director
on <i>Mission to Mars</i>

01:37:46.487 --> 01:37:49.782
and he came with a budget
of $115 million.

01:37:49.865 --> 01:37:52.367
And they said, "No,
we can't make it at that."

01:37:52.451 --> 01:37:55.788
So, I walked into that picture
where everybody was sort of hired.

01:37:55.871 --> 01:37:57.831
Literally, there was
a whole staff there

01:37:57.915 --> 01:38:01.877
and I started storyboarding
the big set pieces immediately.

01:38:01.960 --> 01:38:03.378
But it was like, relentless,

01:38:03.462 --> 01:38:07.049
I mean, because it was so many
of those really complicated shots

01:38:07.132 --> 01:38:09.176
and I had to think up
all these sequences.

01:38:09.259 --> 01:38:10.594
We basically ran out of money.

01:38:10.677 --> 01:38:12.638
Those shots
are so expensive.

01:38:12.721 --> 01:38:14.598
You do one of those shots
the first day

01:38:14.681 --> 01:38:16.266
and you're seeing it
every week

01:38:16.350 --> 01:38:19.436
as they add one
incremental thing to it.

01:38:19.520 --> 01:38:21.939
And that goes on for a year,
basically.

01:38:22.022 --> 01:38:24.775
I mean, I was always amazed that
people were able to do these things,

01:38:24.900 --> 01:38:26.860
like Steven or Zemeckis.

01:38:26.944 --> 01:38:30.697
I mean, holy mackerel,
endless repetition.

01:38:30.781 --> 01:38:32.032
♪♪

01:38:32.116 --> 01:38:33.492
But you have
to stay with it,

01:38:33.575 --> 01:38:35.160
you know,
it's all this pressure.

01:38:35.244 --> 01:38:37.788
Everybody's trying
to save themselves basically.

01:38:37.913 --> 01:38:39.123
When it gets so big,

01:38:39.206 --> 01:38:42.084
nobody wants to be the father
of this huge thing.

01:38:42.167 --> 01:38:45.712
And if it doesn't work out,
you know, heads are going to roll.

01:38:45.796 --> 01:38:48.590
Though I love some of the stuff
I did in it.

01:38:48.674 --> 01:38:50.318
You know, it's like,
"What am I doing here?

01:38:50.342 --> 01:38:54.138
I'm trying to beat a budget,
a schedule with sort of a—"

01:38:54.221 --> 01:38:56.140
You know, I sort of got in way
over my head

01:38:56.223 --> 01:39:01.478
because it was so much work
for such a long period of time.

01:39:01.562 --> 01:39:05.232
And then you think,
"Am I really enjoying this?

01:39:05.315 --> 01:39:07.943
You know, I just turned 60.

01:39:09.528 --> 01:39:12.698
This— Is this— Is this what
I want to be doing?"

01:39:12.781 --> 01:39:16.618
The Hollywood system we work in,
it does nothing but destroy you.

01:39:16.702 --> 01:39:19.496
There's nothing good about it
in terms of creativity.

01:39:19.580 --> 01:39:22.958
So, you're battling
a very difficult system,

01:39:23.041 --> 01:39:27.629
and all the values
of that system are the opposite of—

01:39:27.713 --> 01:39:30.966
to what goes into making original,
good movies.

01:39:31.049 --> 01:39:32.634
When I finished that movie,

01:39:32.718 --> 01:39:34.558
that's when I got on a plane
and went to Paris.

01:39:34.636 --> 01:39:36.930
I said, "I don't want to make movies
like this anymore."

01:39:37.014 --> 01:39:38.473
So, <i>Mission to Mars</i>

01:39:38.557 --> 01:39:41.226
was the last movie
I made in the United States.

01:39:41.310 --> 01:39:43.979
That's the upside of being a loner,
for the most part.

01:39:44.062 --> 01:39:47.357
You can suddenly say,
"This isn't working."

01:39:49.193 --> 01:39:50.736
Well,
I love to make movies

01:39:50.819 --> 01:39:56.074
that are basically created
on pure cinematic ideas.

01:39:56.158 --> 01:39:59.411
<i>Femme Fatale</i> is all about
visual construction in storytelling.

01:39:59.494 --> 01:40:01.371
I'm a very polarizing figure

01:40:01.455 --> 01:40:05.167
and the critics just thought
I was just hopeless and a hack.

01:40:05.250 --> 01:40:06.752
And then
there are the critics

01:40:06.835 --> 01:40:08.545
that sort of understood
what I was doing,

01:40:08.629 --> 01:40:10.088
at least I felt they did.

01:40:10.172 --> 01:40:14.009
It never sort of bothered me
when they didn't like the movies,

01:40:14.092 --> 01:40:15.844
because they were, you know,

01:40:15.928 --> 01:40:20.057
seemingly unkind to women
or too violent or—

01:40:20.140 --> 01:40:21.900
I just felt, to me,
it was always seemed like

01:40:21.934 --> 01:40:23.810
the right thing to do
for the material.

01:40:23.894 --> 01:40:25.494
You know, the fact that Pauline liked me

01:40:25.562 --> 01:40:28.190
made people argue
about me constantly.

01:40:28.273 --> 01:40:30.275
♪♪

01:40:38.867 --> 01:40:43.956
I have a kind of very complicated,
intricate way of looking at things.

01:40:44.039 --> 01:40:48.543
I have to force myself to work
in very straight lines

01:40:48.627 --> 01:40:52.547
because, believe me,
when it gets in my hands,

01:40:52.631 --> 01:40:55.175
it's going to start
getting twisted

01:40:55.259 --> 01:40:59.846
and seen through reflections
and refractions.

01:41:01.473 --> 01:41:03.141
A lot of creating suspense

01:41:03.225 --> 01:41:07.396
is creating distraction
from the impending tragedy.

01:41:07.479 --> 01:41:08.790
You know,
it's like a magic trick.

01:41:08.814 --> 01:41:10.148
You want them to look
at this hand

01:41:10.232 --> 01:41:12.025
while the other hand
is doing something.

01:41:12.109 --> 01:41:16.613
So, you have to create
a whole texture

01:41:16.697 --> 01:41:20.200
that draws the audience's eye
away from the rabbit

01:41:20.284 --> 01:41:22.077
that you're pulling out of a hat.

01:41:22.160 --> 01:41:26.248
♪♪

01:41:26.331 --> 01:41:29.376
[brakes screeching]

01:41:33.255 --> 01:41:34.506
[groans]

01:41:42.222 --> 01:41:43.974
<i>The Black Dahlia</i> was an example

01:41:44.099 --> 01:41:46.518
of where,
unlike <i>Bonfire the Vanities,</i>

01:41:46.601 --> 01:41:49.313
I said, "I'm just going to do
<i>The Black Dahlia</i>

01:41:49.396 --> 01:41:51.273
the way
<i>The Black Dahlia</i> is

01:41:51.356 --> 01:41:53.942
and like a lot of those
Dashiell Hammett mysteries

01:41:54.026 --> 01:41:56.194
that nobody
can quite understand."

01:41:56.278 --> 01:41:59.448
I said, "I guess that's part
of this genre."

01:41:59.531 --> 01:42:00.866
[laughs]

01:42:00.949 --> 01:42:03.577
I said, "I'm going to try to follow

01:42:03.660 --> 01:42:06.246
the original novel
and all its complexities,"

01:42:06.330 --> 01:42:08.999
and of course, everybody says
about <i>The Black Dahlia,</i>

01:42:09.124 --> 01:42:10.417
they can't follow anything.

01:42:11.626 --> 01:42:14.838
I started prepping it
in Los Angeles, where it takes place.

01:42:14.921 --> 01:42:16.173
Then we went to Germany,

01:42:16.256 --> 01:42:19.134
then we wound up going to Italy
and prepping it there.

01:42:19.217 --> 01:42:20.927
And we wound up being
in Bulgaria,

01:42:21.011 --> 01:42:25.098
where we finally got the final piece
of financing to get the movie made.

01:42:25.182 --> 01:42:29.019
If I'm going to put somebody
in a dangerous situation,

01:42:29.144 --> 01:42:32.606
I'd rather be following around
a girl than a guy.

01:42:32.689 --> 01:42:34.358
It's part of the genre.

01:42:34.441 --> 01:42:35.859
The woman
with the negligee

01:42:35.942 --> 01:42:38.236
walking around the house
with a candelabra.

01:42:38.320 --> 01:42:39.905
You see
in a lot of my movies.

01:42:39.988 --> 01:42:42.908
You see the character's helplessness
to stop this—

01:42:42.991 --> 01:42:45.160
this madness going on.

01:42:45.243 --> 01:42:48.372
I lived in a family full of these
incredible egotists

01:42:48.455 --> 01:42:49.998
who seemed to be
very insensitive

01:42:50.082 --> 01:42:52.918
about the kind of damage
they were doing to each other

01:42:53.001 --> 01:42:55.879
and my middle brother
is very sensitive.

01:42:55.962 --> 01:42:59.674
I don't feel that he was powerful enough
to stand up to these forces.

01:42:59.758 --> 01:43:02.719
I used to protect him
all the time.

01:43:02.803 --> 01:43:05.555
He doesn't have the kind of combativeness
that I have.

01:43:05.639 --> 01:43:08.058
So, it would be like this little kid
trying to say,

01:43:08.183 --> 01:43:10.602
"Stop shouting,
it's not his fault."

01:43:10.685 --> 01:43:12.246
And nobody would pay
any attention to me,

01:43:12.270 --> 01:43:13.814
and I was
basically ineffective,

01:43:13.897 --> 01:43:16.191
and I became very tough
because of that.

01:43:16.274 --> 01:43:17.526
Slow down! Slow it down.

01:43:17.609 --> 01:43:19.027
- [man] Hey. Hey, hey.
- Slow down!

01:43:19.111 --> 01:43:20.630
[De Palma]
You know, the story of <i>Redacted</i>

01:43:20.654 --> 01:43:22.374
is basically the story
of <i>Casualties of War,</i>

01:43:22.406 --> 01:43:24.300
you know, these things
that sort make no sense to you,

01:43:24.324 --> 01:43:28.161
like, "Why are we in Vietnam?"
or "Why are we in Iraq?"

01:43:28.245 --> 01:43:30.997
And we're worried about Iraq's
weapons of mass destruction

01:43:31.081 --> 01:43:35.168
after we have completely destroyed
their army in a prior war.

01:43:35.252 --> 01:43:37.212
They have no air force.

01:43:37.295 --> 01:43:39.840
We've been starving them
to death for a decade or so.

01:43:39.923 --> 01:43:42.008
[speaking Arabic]

01:43:42.092 --> 01:43:44.719
[De Palma] Well, Zahra played
the part of the girl

01:43:44.803 --> 01:43:47.472
that gets raped
in <i>Redacted.</i>

01:43:47.556 --> 01:43:50.308
And she was a refugee,
you know, living in Amman.

01:43:50.392 --> 01:43:52.727
But I'm dealing with a culture
I don't understand,

01:43:52.811 --> 01:43:56.148
so when we had her do
all this stuff, you know,

01:43:56.231 --> 01:43:57.983
like the soldiers pretending
to rape her,

01:43:58.066 --> 01:44:01.570
I mean, I don't know what kind of cultural
mores I'm crossing here,

01:44:01.653 --> 01:44:03.905
but this—
Zahra was very understanding

01:44:03.989 --> 01:44:06.908
and did the kind of things
that I asked her to do,

01:44:06.992 --> 01:44:10.245
and I felt that she was really
going out on a limb here.

01:44:10.328 --> 01:44:12.831
These are things that her family,
upon seeing the movie,

01:44:12.914 --> 01:44:14.166
were horrified by.

01:44:14.249 --> 01:44:20.338
I mean, she's kind of been
rejected by her whole culture.

01:44:20.422 --> 01:44:24.176
But she's an actress
and she felt that this was right.

01:44:24.259 --> 01:44:26.428
And I got her into it, basically,

01:44:26.511 --> 01:44:28.054
because I'm the one
that directed her.

01:44:28.138 --> 01:44:32.517
And then rather than leave her there
with a very uncertain future,

01:44:32.601 --> 01:44:36.062
and because she's a talented girl
and a very wonderful girl,

01:44:36.146 --> 01:44:38.565
I brought her over here
and put her in school

01:44:38.648 --> 01:44:41.359
so that she can pursue her dream,
whatever it is.

01:44:41.610 --> 01:44:43.445
♪♪

01:44:44.529 --> 01:44:47.574
Well, I think I'm returning to the kind
of movies you guys are making.

01:44:47.657 --> 01:44:48.992
You're adjusting to the system.

01:44:49.075 --> 01:44:53.872
If you want to make personal movies,
with your own personal ideas,

01:44:53.955 --> 01:44:56.750
you have to make them
at a budget.

01:44:56.833 --> 01:44:58.502
You make
a certain kind of movie

01:44:58.585 --> 01:45:01.087
because that's the way
you see things.

01:45:01.171 --> 01:45:06.092
And these images keep reoccurring again
and again in your movies.

01:45:06.176 --> 01:45:08.428
And that's what makes you
who you are.

01:45:08.512 --> 01:45:10.514
♪♪

01:45:14.601 --> 01:45:16.895
People talk about Hitchcock
all the time,

01:45:16.978 --> 01:45:19.356
you know,
being so influential.

01:45:19.439 --> 01:45:22.025
I've never found
too many people

01:45:22.108 --> 01:45:24.986
that followed after the Hitchcock school
except for me.

01:45:25.070 --> 01:45:26.404
Here's a guy that developed

01:45:26.488 --> 01:45:29.324
those incredible visual
storytelling vocabulary,

01:45:29.407 --> 01:45:31.284
and it's sort of going
to die with him.

01:45:31.368 --> 01:45:33.995
And I was like,
the one practitioner

01:45:34.079 --> 01:45:36.873
that took up the things
that he pioneered

01:45:36.957 --> 01:45:40.752
and built them into different forms
in a style that I was evolving.

01:45:40.835 --> 01:45:43.421
It's like a whole modern form
that he created.

01:45:43.505 --> 01:45:45.215
Having studied
a lot of directors

01:45:45.340 --> 01:45:49.594
and having lived now
to practically being 70,

01:45:49.678 --> 01:45:52.222
you see that
your creative periods are in—

01:45:52.347 --> 01:45:54.683
most directors' are in—
in their 30s,

01:45:54.766 --> 01:45:57.185
their 40s,
and their 50s.

01:45:57.269 --> 01:45:59.688
They, and obviously,
they can go on

01:45:59.771 --> 01:46:03.024
and make another 20 movies
or 10 movies,

01:46:03.108 --> 01:46:05.944
but you'll probably only be
talking about those movies

01:46:06.027 --> 01:46:09.239
they made in their 30s,
their 40s, and their 50s.

01:46:09.364 --> 01:46:12.450
You know, and I've always thought
Hitchcock was a great example,

01:46:12.534 --> 01:46:16.705
because, you know,
after <i>Vertigo</i> and <i>Psycho,</i>

01:46:16.788 --> 01:46:19.874
and you can talk about
<i>The Birds</i> all you want

01:46:19.958 --> 01:46:21.835
and all the other movies
he made after that

01:46:21.918 --> 01:46:25.839
and then of course, the critical
establishment finally caught up with him

01:46:25.922 --> 01:46:29.509
and started to write about
what a genius he was.

01:46:29.593 --> 01:46:31.428
Except those movies
aren't as good

01:46:31.511 --> 01:46:35.932
as the ones he made
in his 30s, his 40s, and his 50s.

01:46:36.016 --> 01:46:38.018
♪♪

01:46:39.269 --> 01:46:43.273
You got to be a strong,
physical person to do it.

01:46:43.398 --> 01:46:46.484
It physically wears you down.
There's no question about it.

01:46:46.568 --> 01:46:48.570
I think William Wilder said,
you know,

01:46:48.653 --> 01:46:50.947
"When you can't walk anymore,
you've got to stop."

01:46:52.282 --> 01:46:53.658
The thing about making movies

01:46:53.742 --> 01:46:56.494
is every mistake you made
is up there on the screen.

01:46:56.578 --> 01:47:00.248
Everything you didn't solve,
every shortcut you made,

01:47:00.332 --> 01:47:02.375
you will look at it
the rest of your life.

01:47:02.459 --> 01:47:07.047
So, it's like a record
of the things

01:47:07.130 --> 01:47:09.424
that you didn't finish, basically.

01:47:11.760 --> 01:47:16.264
People in your life can be threatened
by your intense concentration,

01:47:16.348 --> 01:47:19.392
your complete immersion
in what you're doing.

01:47:19.476 --> 01:47:21.895
My true wife is my movie,
not you.

01:47:21.978 --> 01:47:23.980
[music playing]

01:48:21.746 --> 01:48:23.748
♪♪
